    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the advice. i thought maybe it was nitrogen though? i read online that old leaves turning yellow is a classic sign of nitrogen deficiency. if it is nitrogen, how do i check my soil ph to make sure the plants can actually use the nutrients i'm giving them?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're correct that yellowing leaves can be a sign of nitrogen deficiency, especially when it starts at the older leaves. Low soil pH can indeed limit the availability of nutrients to your plants, including nitrogen. To check your soil pH, you can perform a simple DIY test: dig a small hole, fill it with water, and observe how quickly the water drains. If the water drains quickly, your soil pH is likely acidic (below 6.0). If it takes a while, your soil is probably neutral to slightly alkaline (6.0-7.0), while slow draining water may indicate a highly alkaline soil (above 7.0).",
